{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "This article provides a comprehensive reconstruction of Cugoano's moral and legal philosophy in order to analyse an apparent tension in his abolitionism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "In this work dedicated to the 'total abolition of slavery' Cugoano defends on principled grounds the legitimacy of enslaving human beings in punishment (98).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Belief in the legitimacy of penal bondage was surprisingly widespread among abolitionist thinkers writing in late eighteenth-century Britain.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Cugoano - the most radical antislavery theorist in the period - regarded penal enslavement of both ordinary criminals and colonial enslavers as justifiable in principle, I will show.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Amidst the growing literature exploring Cugoano's abolitionism, his paradoxical justification of penal slavery has bewildered the few commentators attentive to it.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "This article offers the first full reconstruction of the nature, grounds, and theoretical implications of Cugoano's justification of penal bondage.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "The problem of penal slavery, I contend, runs much deeper in his abolitionism than has been previously recognized.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Pace Bogues, I argue that this justification is an integral part of his moral and legal theory.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Pace Bernasconi and Shanafelt, I contend that Cugoano's defence of penal slavery goes beyond retaliation against European enslavers.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Comparisons of his justification of penal bondage with the rival ones of Locke and Kant indicate just how deeply theories of punishment shaped philosophical thinking on penal bondage in the period.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Punishment for crime was the most widely accepted apologetic ground for enslavement of human beings among early modern philosophers.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Many early modern philosophers reconciled universal natural rights with penal enslavement by conceptualizing those rights as wholly forfeitable through grave wrongdoing.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "For Cugoano, the sole legitimate ground for enslavement is grave wrongdoing.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Cugoano's theory of law and punishment, I maintain, rests squarely upon a divine law theory of ethics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "The law of God is a revealed one, laid down in the Bible.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Above all, it dictates love and charity.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "The Bible contains a basic law of punishment, consisting of two parts.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Justice states that wrongdoers deserve punishment equal to their crime - eye for an eye, tooth for tooth.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Yet mercy is morally required when inflicting like-for-like punishment on deserving offenders serves no social good.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "Cugoano sometimes invokes the law of love to denounce modern colonial slavery.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Cugoano accuses slaveholders and slave-traders of robbery.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Crime warrants punishment.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "Civil law must implement and enforce the divine law.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "The need for civil law to match divine law underpins Cugoano's rhetorically most powerful appeal for immediate and total abolition.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "The lex talionis is rather unpopular among legal philosophers today.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Repugnant as applying the lex talionis to monstrosities like slavery is, it is surprising that this retaliatory principle figures prominently in the British Enlightenment's most radical abolitionist treatise, written by someone once enslaved himself.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "Cugoano's justification of penal enslavement serves retaliatory purposes alone: 'if one enslaves someone unjustly, then one should oneself be enslaved'.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU28": {
      "text": "Cugoano endorses penal enslavement for a much wider set of crimes than enslavement of innocents alone.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU29": {
      "text": "The divine law of mercy tempers just retaliation: inflicting the punishment malefactors deserve is morally permissible only if it promotes some social good.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU30": {
      "text": "Thoughts and Sentiments cites several potential benefits of civil punishment in general, and of penal enslavement in particular.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU31": {
      "text": "Penal enslavement is morally permissible only insofar as it produces amends to victims, deters crime, or morally corrects the offender.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU32": {
      "text": "The divine law of forbearance not only delimits when penal enslavement is morally permissible.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU33": {
      "text": "It also attenuates the condition of penal bondage.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU34": {
      "text": "Cugoano's abolitionist arguments are complicated, however, by his principled endorsement of the legitimacy of penal slavery.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU35": {
      "text": "Cugoano develops two facially contradictory lines of argument to ensure that justified penal bondage does not undercut his abolitionism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU36": {
      "text": "Cugoano could coherently permit the sale of enslaved convicts while denouncing the injustice of colonial slavery and the slave-trade, by transforming the legal condition of convicts sold to outsiders into something like indentured servitude.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU37": {
      "text": "Full eradication of human bondage was not just a practical but also a theoretical struggle for Enlightenment abolitionists.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU38": {
      "text": "Justice sometimes requires penally enslaving the enslavers in turn - life for life, bondage for bondage.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU39": {
      "text": "The biblical laws of retaliation and forbearance jointly set a universal standard for due punishment, determining when and how to punish crimes.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU40": {
      "text": "The prevalence of philosophical justifications of penal slavery evinces, furthermore, that Enlightenment conceptions of natural rights differ considerably from modern human rights.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
