{
  "ADUs": {
    "1": {
      "text": "Notwithstanding this, Cugoano endorsed the legitimacy of penal enslavement on principled grounds - like many other abolitionists writing in late eighteenth-century Britain. 'Every free community might keep slaves, or criminal prisoners in bondage' - and even sell them.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "2": {
      "text": "Far from an offhand inconsistency, I argue that this justification is deeply embedded within his moral and legal philosophy; constraining his antislavery arguments while simultaneously serving retaliatory aims.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "3": {
      "text": "His two-pronged principle of just punishment - the lex talionis ('eye for an eye, bondage for bondage') as tempered by mercy - sometimes demands penally enslaving colonial slaveholders and slave-traders in turn.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "Divine lawgiving has created morality. Without God, there would have been no moral right and wrong.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "Justice states that wrongdoers deserve punishment equal to their crime - eye for an eye, tooth for tooth. Yet mercy is morally required when inflicting like-for-like punishment on deserving offenders serves no social good.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "Having committed a crime deserving of punishment is for him a necessary but not a sufficient condition for permissible punishment. Indeed, the law of forbearance forbids purely retaliatory punishment, done for the sake of vengeance alone.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "To be morally permissible, punishment must bring some 'reparation or benefit to ourselves'.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
